\subtree{
\title{Output Formats}
\p{The API supports two primary output formats:}

\ul{
\li{\strong{JSON} (default): Machine-readable format, ideal for programmatic access}
\li{\strong{TXT}: Human-readable tab-delimited text format}
}

\p{Specify format by appending \code{\startverb /json\stopverb} or \code{\startverb /txt\stopverb} to API URLs. When format is omitted, JSON is returned by default.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Use RefMet for standardization}: Always standardize metabolite names through RefMet before searching studies to ensure consistent nomenclature}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Specify appropriate adducts}: When performing m/z searches, use the correct ion adduct type for your analytical method (e.g., M+H for positive mode ESI)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Set reasonable tolerances}: Use appropriate mass tolerance values (typically 0.5 Da for low-resolution, 0.01 Da for high-resolution MS)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Cache reference data}: Consider caching frequently used reference data (RefMet database, compound information) to minimize API calls}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Handle pagination}: For large result sets, be prepared to handle multiple data structures in responses}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Validate identifiers}: Cross-reference metabolite identifiers across multiple databases when possible to ensure correct compound identification}
}
}

